But I am afraid, if we come to examin the Matter a little more cloſely, we ſhall find that this is generally

all Stratagem; and that my Worthy Brethren who make uſe of it, have an odd Way of impoſing upon the World, and giving of it one Term for another: Their pretended Gravity ſhould be call'd Natural Dulneſs, for 'tis ſo in Fact; and where there is Fire, it will ſhew itſelf: Their Pretence to Religion, in Oppoſition to Human Reaſon, is not becauſe they have more of the Firſt than their Neighbours, but leſs of the Latter: Their Canting Cuſtom of Asking a peculiar Bleſſing on every Thing they undertake, is becauſe they know their Skill will ſtand very much in Need of it: Their Diſaffection to Human Learning is, becauſe they know Nothing more of it than the Name; and ſo of every Thing elſe;

In ſhort, I am tir'd of them; but I'll beg Leave to ſay, they are very pretty People to truſt Mens Lives and Limbs with.
